We next consider the edge $uv$. By slightly perturbing the drawing in a neighbourhood of $v$ we can move $v$ into the outer domain. Then, by construction, in the diagram of the edge $vu$, the first two edges of the musquash ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$ that $uv$ crosses, counting from $v$, are incident to the same vertex of ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$. What is more, as $v$ lies in the outer domain, the starting segment $uB^1, \; B^1 \in C$, of the diagram of $uv$ has to be chosen in such a way that the complement to the set of edges of ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$ which it crosses is a union of even paths. From \eqref{eq:V5u} we see that this is only possible for the first two vectors, so that  $uB^1$ only crosses a single edge. The choice of that edge determines the diagram of $uv$ uniquely by the fact that the remaining straight lines segment in it are short segments close to the vertices of ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$ crossing pairs of edges incident to those vertices. We can now add the diagram of $uv$ to the diagram of $wu$ on the left in Figure~\ref{figure:diagrams5} in the three possible ways shown in Figure \ref{figure:5uvw1}, where in the diagram on the right in Figure~\ref{figure:5uvw1}, there are two possible ways of adding the segment $B^4B^5$. Now, in the diagram on the left in Figure~\ref{figure:5uvw1}, the point $B^1$ can only be connected to $B^4$, and then the only way to make a thrackle pass is to join $B^4$ to $B^3$ \emph{inside} the disc $D$, going around the point $w$. But then the last two crossings on the edge $uv$ counting from $u$ are not with two consecutive edges of ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$, and so the edge $uv$ cannot be deformed to one attached to a vertex of ${\mathcal{T}}(c)$. In the diagram in the middle in Figure~\ref{figure:5uvw1}, the point $B^1$ cannot be joined to any other point $B^j$. In the diagram on the right in Figure~\ref{figure:5uvw1}, the segment $B^2B^3$ is unreachable from the point $B^1$, no matter which of two possibilities for segment $B^4B^5$ are chosen.

